post_text:
This was shared by one of our Middle School teachers. I hope you all find it as inspiring as we do.

"Teaching is now experiencing a change just like music experienced from the 70’s to the 2000’s. We went from records, to 8-tracks, to cassettes (Walkmans/Boom Boxes), CD’s, and ended up with digital downloads. But music didn’t go away. The sounds, feelings, energy, and emotional response that music brings didn’t go away. Only the platform changed.

It’s only our platform that will change as teachers. After music went through all of its changes it actually became more accessible, more integrated and more important to everyday life than before. Society doesn’t know it, but teachers just became more accessible, more integrated and more important to a child’s life than ever before."

RFISD Parents,

In an effort to better plan for school meals during the period of time students will be learning from home, RFISD Food Services is seeking your input. Please take a moment to complete a very brief survey at https://forms.gle/47hk94ZS2KrGMF6M6. This survey will help the Randolph Field Food Services Department determine if there is an interest in prepared meals for Randolph Field ISD students. Any meals provided will be distributed grab and go, in a drive-through setting. A new meal ordering app will available to place orders.

Meals will be available to students during remote instruction, and will continue for students who choose to remain in an online learning environment after students are allowed to return to campus.

Thank you,

Cynthia Moczygemba
Director of Food Services, RFISD

Summer Athletic Conditioning Program Suspended

On June 23, 2020, RFISD administration was made aware that one of our student athletes participating in the summer conditioning program tested positive for COVID-19. Please know that our athletic staff and athletes have been implementing recommended CDC safety precautions including social distancing and the use of PPE. Out of an abundance of caution, the RFISD summer athletic conditioning program has been suspended until July 6, 2020. If you have any questions, please contact Coach Wesp, RFISD Athletic Director at (210-357-2473) or wesp@rfisd.net.

post_text:
A Message from Dr. Holt

Randolph Field ISD Families:

Our goals during these uncertain times are to protect our students and deliver the best education possible. You can rest assured that we are planning for multiple contingencies in an effort to educate RFISD students better than ever! We have asked for your partnership during these times and the parents and families of RFISD have delivered. 100% of our Senior class graduated and our students continued to show academic growth at every grade level. Once again, we are asking for your input. On Thursday, June 18, campus principals will send a survey. Please take a few minutes to respond.

I hope all of you are well and I pray that your spirit is strong. We live and work in a community of heroes. The faculty and staff are very appreciative of your sacrifice, support, and fellowship.

Best Regards,
Dr. Holt

post_text: Please join us in welcoming Dr. Brian Holt as the new Superintendent of Randolph Field ISD. Dr. Holt brings more than two decades of experience as an educator and administrator in every level of education, from pre-kindergarten through university. Dr. Holt most recently served as Superintendent of Schools for Booker ISD from 2016 until his acceptance of this position with RFISD. Throughout his career in education, Dr. Holt has demonstrated a high level of leadership and a track record of success. He has earned the respect and confidence of his colleagues and peers. Dr. Holt will officially join the RFISD community on May 1 and will be sending out a message within the next couple of weeks. We are excited to welcome him and his family to RFISD.

post_text: This afternoon, Gov. Greg Abbott ordered Texas schools closed through May 1. This was not the news we were hoping for but understand that it is in the best interest of our families, teachers, and staff. We know this adds another week to what is a very challenging situation. We are listening. We will continue to work hard to partner with you to continue student learning. We have always said that student learning and adult learning go hand in hand. That has never been more true than now. Please continue to reach out to teachers and campus administration and let us know how we can help. Also, let your children know we miss them and look forward to seeing them as soon as possible.

post_text:
Randolph Field ISD is extending the period of time we will be providing remote learning through Friday, April 24. We make this difficult decision in our continued attempt to keep students and staff safe and to comply with guidance from local officials. During this time, district and campus staff will remain accessible through phone, email, and social media but district facilities will be closed to visitors unless permission has been given by the district or campus.

We will continue to reach out to ensure we are meeting the needs of our families to include maintaining technology devices. We will also continue to keep you updated with any new developments on our website, through social media, and through School Messenger. We hope you and your family are safe and healthy.

Joint Base San Antonio
March 15 at 4:35 PM ·

#JBSA Effective immediately, Defenders will no longer be touching your ID cards, and as you arrive at our installation gates and visitor centers, please follow these 3 steps:

1️⃣. BARCODE - Reach out and display your ID with the barcode side up so it can be scanned.
2️⃣. PICTURE - When prompted, flip over the card with an unobstructed view of the front side.
3️⃣. WAIT - Please DO NOT proceed through the gate until directed to do so by the Defender.

We also recommend that you allow for additional travel time as we implement this change, and we thank you for your patience! This is to minimize contact, reduce the spread of COVID-19, and to keep our JBSA community safe.

Education Solutions and Services, the search committee chosen by the Board of Trustees of RFISD, is soliciting input from staff, parents, and community as they seek out the best candidate for Superintendent of the district. Please take a moment to complete this short survey found at https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/GNPTN2N in order to provide input on this very important decision. If you would prefer an opportunity to offer your feedback in a face-to-face setting you may meet with them from 5:00-6:00pm on Wednesday, January 8, in the Early Childhood Center at Randolph Elementary School. The Early Childhood Center is located on New B Street at the back of the main elementary campus.

SURVEYMONKEY.COM
Randolph Field ISD Superintendent Search

Randolph Elementary has seats available for non-resident transfer students at the following grade levels: Kindergarten, Grade 2, Grade 3, and Grade 5. If you are interested in submitting a transfer application for review, please follow the link below, or contact Matty Salinas at salinas@rfisd.net. Priority is given to active duty dependents, but all families who have access to the base are welcomed to submit an application. Once a student is accepted, priority placement is given to continuously enrolled active duty dependents in subsequent years. Please note, RFISD does not provide transportation to transfer students to and from school.

After weeks of progressing through a blended learning professional development course that included weekly readings, videos, and assignments, seven RFISD educators have successfully passed the Google Educator Level 1 certification exam.

Designed for educators and classroom teachers who wish to demonstrate proficiency in using Google for Education tools, the Level 1 status indicates that an educator is able to successfully implement G Suite for Education into their teaching practice in order to enhance teaching and learning.

Congratulations to the following RFISD teachers on earning your Google Educator Level 1 Certification:

Michelle Benites (Randolph Middle School)
Amy Byrd (Randolph Elementary School)
Kourtney Carruthers (Randolph Elementary School)
Kevin Miller (Randolph Middle School)
Kalee Peacock (Randolph Middle School)
Ana Rosas-Saunders (Randolph High School)
Connie Ann Roussel (Randolph Elementary School)

post_text: Day 2 of the RFISD STEAM Camp was definitely as fun as the first day. Students worked with video and green screens to create commercials for the shoes they have designed, everyone had a good time during our extended lunch hour field trip, and ideation and design work has begun on their next challenge...building a cardboard arcade!

post_text: Day 1 of the RFISD STEAM Camp was a tremendous success! Our students learned about design thinking, spoke with a product designer (and former Ro-Hawk) from Under Armour via Google Hangouts, learned about circuitry and coding, designed their own sneaker, and had a good time all around. Can’t wait to share the fun and learning in store throughout the rest of the week!

Is your child interested in STEM? For over a decade, Girls Inc. of San Antonio has held the Girls RockIT Into the Future Science Festival. Celebrating science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM), this Science Festival provides girls and their families with the opportunity to meet with local experts, enjoy hands-on experiments, and partake in STEM activities in an encouraging environment. This opportunity provides girls (of all ages) the opportunity to excel in STEM and the chance to pursue their passions.

Last year, Girls Inc., hosted over 35 exhibitors that brought over 80 hands-on, minds-on activities for 2,400 people that enjoy the festival for free.

Event Details are:

Date: SATURDAY, MAY 11, 2019

Time: 10am – 2pm

Location:
Mission County Park
6030 Padre Dr.,
San Antonio, TX 78214

TRANSFER FORMS FOR 2018-2019 ARE NOW AVAILABLE FOR DOWNLOAD.

2018-2019 transfer applications will be accepted by e-mail at transfers@rfisd.net or faxed to (210) 357-2469 starting at 8:00 a.m. May 1, 2018. Applications may also be mailed directly to P.O. Box 2217, Universal City, TX 78148.

Beginning at 8 a.m. May 2, 2018, applications may be dropped off in person at the Superintendent's office (office closes at 4:00 p.m. each day).

Each application will be stamped with the date and time it is received. All incomplete applications will be denied until required documentation is provided.

For additional information or questions please contact us at transfers@rfisd.net

The 2018-19 transfer packet can be found at the district website http://rfisd.net.

JBSA Middle School Students and Parents!

We are thrilled to offer your middle school children a chance to attend MicroSoft's YouthSpark Live event on Friday, June 1st. YouthSpark Live is a global community enabling youth to collaborate, inspire, and support each other while using technology to spark change. Participants in this event can expect:

Hands-on experience with cutting-edge technologies, including:
- Microprocessors and drones
- Mentorship from technology professionals
- Inspiring talks from community leaders
- Prizes, surprises, and more!

This event is FREE and open to any CURRENT 6th-8th grade student at Cole MS, Randolph MS, or Stacey MS. Breakfast, lunch, t-shirts, materials, and supplies will be provided. It will take place at Cole Middle School from 8:30am until 2:00pm. Space is limited so register TODAY!

You can register online at http://fshisd.link/YouthSparkLive2018

If you have any questions, you can email Mrs. Daniels at daniels@rfisd.net or Dr. Rios at rrios@fshisd.net.

Randolph Middle School, TX

We want to invite you to celebrate #RAKWeek2018 (February 11-17, 2018) by telling us about that one person who inspires you to be a better human being!

• Was it a teacher who saw something in you when no one else did?
• Is it a neighbor who mowed your lawn when you were sick?
• What about a family member who always encouraged you to do your best?
• Maybe it was your friend who comforted you during a difficult time in your life?

We all have someone who has gone above and beyond to show us kindness; someone who shifts our perspective, helps us through painful moments or inspires us to be kinder in our daily lives.

TO CELEBRATE RAK WEEK, SNAP A PHOTO OF THAT PERSON AND SHARE THEIR STORY WITH US IN THE COMMENTS!

If you can’t get a photo of your 'one', share a photo of something that represents their amazing qualities. While you’re at it, how about doing an act of kindness EVERY DAY during #RAKWeek2018 in their honor? What better way to pay tribute to the difference they made in your life? Now it’s your chance to make a difference in someone else’s life. Let’s do this Ro-Hawks!

https://sites.google.com/a/rfisd.net/registration-information/

Returning student registration for students in grades K-12 in Randolph Field ISD will again be completed online for the 2017-2018 school year. This process will be completed through our current online gradebook/attendance program, txConnect, as well as Chalk Schools, an electronic document/signature service and will be available beginning April 3, 2017.

Information regarding the requirements for online registration, as well as a link to a “how to document” for completing online student registration are available at: https://sites.google.com/a/rfisd.net/registration-information/

Please note, the online registration process is NOT the same as the non-resident transfer application. A transfer application must be submitted for all students who do not reside on Randolph Air Force Base.

We are partnering with BrightBytes, an educational research organization, in order to learn more about our students’ school and home technology use for learning. We are reaching out to ask you to take part in a Technology & Learning survey. Your participation is essential in helping us form a more complete picture of technology use for learning in our students’ lives. The surveys will take approximately 5 minutes to complete.

Randolph Elementary www.BByt.es/HG3YP
Randolph Middle www.BByt.es/BU7HP
Randolph High www.BByt.es/PE8DP

The last day to complete this questionnaire is November 18, 2016. Please complete the questionnaire by visiting the website(s) above. Please complete this survey for each campus in which you have students enrolled. Please know that all of your responses will remain anonymous to protect your privacy.

Congratulations to RHS teacher Mrs. Nicole Bernal for being selected as the KENS 5 ExCEL Award winner from Randolph Field ISD! post_text:
From Coach Phillips:

Attached is a photo of both the Randolph and Cole High School Lady Cross Country Teams. After their winning runs, both teams came together to congratulate each other on going to state!

This year, the hot sun, temperature, and humidity were factors that stressed all of the regional runners. Every course is different and this course had some rolling hills, coupled with long, straight paths.

Despite these factors, Alex E. won first place and is the Regional Gold Medal Champion with a 2-mile time of 11:58.

State bound team Ro-Hawk 2-mile times were:

Vivian E. 13:32
Mailani G. 14:00
Alicia L. 14:45
Rachelle R. 14:47
Mariah C. 15:25
Taylor D. 15:55

The state meet is in Round Rock at Old Settlers Park on November 12th. Our state team runs at 2:40 and spectator tickets are available through www.tikatap.com.

Go Ro-Hawks!!!

We are once again partnering with BrightBytes, an educational research organization, in order to learn more about our students’ school and home technology use for learning. The BrightBytes initiative has helped us measure our technology growth, and check whether the changes we’re making at school have impacted learning.

We are reaching out to ask you to take part in the Technology & Learning questionnaire. We are once again partnering with BrightBytes, an educational research organization, in order to learn more about our students’ school and home technology use for learning. The BrightBytes initiative has helped us measure our technology growth, and check whether the changes we’re making at school have impacted learning.

We are reaching out to ask you to take part in the Technology & Learning questionnaire. This is an annual initiative, and your participation is essential in helping us form a more complete picture of technology use for learning in your students’ lives. Please know that all of your responses will remain anonymous to protect your privacy.

Over the next few weeks, please keep an eye out for an email with more information on how to participate.
